	<table width="100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	<tr>
	<td class=bodycopy colspan="3"  width="100%">
	
	<P><BR>
	<font class="redsub">Litigation </font><BR>
	Skadden’s Los Angeles litigation department represents clients in high-stakes, high-profile international, national and local litigation.&nbsp; The litigation department has appeared in trial and appellate courts at the federal and state levels, before administrative tribunals, and in arbitrations and other alternative dispute resolution proceedings.&nbsp; Skadden is unmatched in resources and experience, and has earned its reputation as the nation’s premier “go to” firm for complex litigation.&nbsp; At the leading edge of developments in legal strategy and complex case management, Skadden employs top echelon trial advocacy techniques at all stages of litigation, achieving an unparalleled record of successful resolutions across a broad spectrum of high-stakes civil litigation.
<P><b>Securities</b></P>
<P>Our attorneys have represented corporations and their officers and directors, as well as outside professionals (including accountants, attorneys and underwriters), facing large scale, nationwide class and derivative action lawsuits.&nbsp; We have represented companies such as Apartment Investment and Management Company (AIMCO), the directors of The Walt Disney Company, Dove Entertainment, Guess?, Inc., MegaFoods Stores, Inc., Occidental Petroleum Corporation, Oakley, Inc., Pacific Enterprises, Stan Lee Media, Inc., Tenet Healthcare Corporation, Valeant Pharmaceuticals International (f/k/a ICN Pharmaceuticals) and Westfield America Trust in some of the largest class and derivative actions filed in California.&nbsp; In addition, the attorneys in the Los Angeles office were involved in the firm’s representation of a syndicate of the underwriters in the WorldCom, Inc. class action and individual actions arising from the largest-ever corporate bankruptcy.</P>
<P><b>Antitrust</b></P>
<P>Los Angeles antitrust attorneys work on criminal and civil cases in federal and state courts nationwide and advise clients on the antitrust aspects of mergers and acquisitions, joint ventures, treble damage actions, franchising claims and unfair trade practices.&nbsp; Our cases have included the representation of:</P>
<ul>
<li>Christie’s in the criminal and civil auction house price fixing litigation;<BR><BR></li>
<li>Atlantic Richfield in various private and governmental antitrust proceedings relating to mergers and acquisitions, as well as transportation and sale of crude oil and petroleum products;<BR><BR></li>
<li>The National Football League in cases ranging from the USFL’s antitrust challenge, through cases brought by Al Davis and the Raiders with respect to relocation, to cases challenging the joint exploitation of the NFL member clubs’ trademarks;&nbsp;<BR><BR></li>
<li>Home Box Office in an action challenging its motion picture license agreements with studios; and&nbsp;<BR><BR></li>
<li>Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer in a putative class action involving the distribution of its videos.</li></ul>
<P><b>Entertainment and Intellectual Property</b></P>
<P>The Los Angeles office is particularly active in litigation involving the entertainment industry in antitrust, copyright, accounting, plagiarism and contract cases.&nbsp; Our attorneys also handle litigation involving a wide range of intellectual property issues, including trademarks, copyrights, trade secrets, idea misappropriation and unfair competition.&nbsp; Our representation of clients include, among others:</P>
<ul>
<li>Defense of studios, authors and directors in idea misappropriation or plagiarism cases involving motion pictures, including “Something’s Gotta Give,” “Good Morning Vietnam,” “Pretty Woman,” “The Burning Season,” and the television series “Melrose Place”;<BR><BR></li>
<li>Home Box Office in various matters, including its contract dispute with actor James Gandolfini, star of the hit television series “The Sopranos,” and in rights’ litigation over the film “My Big Fat Greek Wedding”;<BR><BR></li>
<li>Warner Music Group and TimeWarner in litigation with Madonna over the joint venture that created Madonna’s Maverick Record Company label;<BR><BR></li>
<li>Disney in copyright and trademark litigation defending its rights to works ranging from the early Mickey Mouse cartoons through the classic “Snow White And The Seven Dwarfs”;&nbsp;<BR><BR></li>
<li>Christie’s auction house in various cases relating to the sale of memorabilia from the life of W.C. Fields, memorabilia from the life of Mohammed Ali, Clark Gable’s “Oscar” from “It Happened One Night,” and an allegedly misattributed Renoir;<BR><BR></li>
<li>Accounting disputes relating to motion pictures, television series and merchandising rights regarding properties, including “What Women Want,” “Lou Grant,” “Win, Lose or Draw,” “The Simpsons,” and the character of Winnie The Pooh;&nbsp;<BR><BR></li>
<li>Guess? in a trademark action over the rights to the Marciano family name;<BR><BR></li>
<li>Century 21 Real Estate Corporation in trademark, false advertising and trade secret litigation brought by Re/Max International, Inc. in which Re/Max sought over $1 billion in damages;<BR><BR></li>
<li>KCAL Television in a copyright infringement claim brought by the owner of the videotape of the beating of Reginald Denny;<BR><BR></li>
<li>KFC in two cases alleging misappropriation of trade secrets, and Taco Bell in actions enforcing its trademarks; and<BR><BR></li>
<li>BPL Films in copyright litigation to prevent the illegal sale and distribution of the movie entitled “The Debtors.”</li></ul>
<P><b>Sports</b></P>
<P>Los Angeles attorneys serve as counsel to a broad spectrum of sports clients on antitrust, corporate, labor and intellectual property matters.&nbsp; We have also participated in the firm’s representation of the National Football League, the National Basketball Association, Major League Baseball and the National Hockey League in player disputes, mergers, acquisitions, venue leases and sponsorship agreements.&nbsp; Examples of our work in this area include:</P>
<ul>
<li>The National Football League in its successful defense against a lawsuit brought by the Oakland Raiders football team alleging that the Raiders were blocked from obtaining a state-of-the-art stadium and were forced to leave Los Angeles and return to Oakland;<BR><BR></li>
<li>Major League Baseball, the National Football League and the National Hockey League in connection with the successful defense of an action involving professional sports trading cards; and<BR><BR></li>
<li>Four universities, each of which is a member of the Big East Conference, in connection with the planned move of several schools to the Atlantic Coast Conference.</li></ul>
<P><b>Energy</b></P>
<P>Members of the Los Angeles litigation department have been involved in advising clients and conducting litigation, administrative proceedings and arbitrations involving some of the most important energy projects in the world.&nbsp; These projects include the representation of:</P>
<ul>
<li>ConocoPhillips in proceedings before the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission and the Regulatory Commission of Alaska regarding accounting among the shippers for the oil shipped on the TransAlaska Pipeline, which brings about 15% of the U.S. domestic production from the North Slope of Alaska to markets in the lower 48 states;<BR><BR></li>
<li>ARCO Alaska with respect to numerous disputes among the parties to the joint venture agreements that govern the fields on the North Slope of Alaska;<BR><BR></li>
<li>Southern Natural Gas Company with respect to antitrust issues regarding access to its interstate pipelines; and<BR><BR></li>
<li>BP with respect to certain rights in Kuwait.</li></ul>
<P><b>Government Enforcement/White Collar Crime</b></P>
<P>Our attorneys have represented corporate and individual clients in white collar criminal matters, including:&nbsp; federal and state grand jury investigations involving securities fraud, money laundering, RICO, health care fraud, qui tam “whistle blower” actions, insider trading violations, and environmental crime investigations.&nbsp; We also conduct internal investigations on behalf of boards of directors and special board committees and defend against qui tam claims.&nbsp; In addition, attorneys in the Los Angeles office have been involved in a wide range of litigation matters under California Business &amp; Professions Code § 17200.</P>
<P><b>International Arbitration</b></P>
<P>A significant portion of the work of the Los Angeles litigation department involves international arbitrations conducted under the laws of various countries pursuant to various arbitral conventions, particularly in the energy and construction defect fields.&nbsp; Representations include:</P>
<ul>
<li>AGIP, British Gas, BP, ConocoPhillips, ExxonMobil, Inpex, Statoil and TotalFinaElf with respect to the development of the huge new Kashagan oil field in the Caspian offshore Kazakhstan;<BR><BR></li>
<li>Chinese National Offshore Oil Corporation, Kuwait Foreign Exploration Company and BP with respect to a large gas field offshore China;<BR><BR></li>
<li>Premier Oil Corporation and Kuwait Foreign Exploration Company with respect to the construction of an undersea pipeline offshore Indonesia; and<BR><BR></li>
<li>First Gas Power Corporation with respect to claims regarding the construction of a power plant in the Philippines.</li></ul>
<P><b>Insurance</b></P>
<P>Skadden Los Angeles represents clients in litigation concerning corporate governance and transactions, insurance coverage and business practices.&nbsp; We provide a broad range of regulatory advice to insurers, reinsurers, investment banks and other companies, including advice as to licensing, securities issuances, investments, solvency, permissible activities and insurance products.&nbsp; Matters in which we have been involved include:</P>
<ul>
<li>State Farm Mutual Automobile Insurance Company in the successful defense of a class action seeking to compel the declaration of more than $6 billion in dividends and to enjoin it from making political contributions;<BR><BR></li>
<li>Farmers Insurance Exchange in defeating the California Attorney General’s action seeking to invalidate settlements entered into by Farmers and other insurers with the California Insurance Commissioner concerning the handling of Northridge earthquake claims; and<BR><BR></li>
<li>Insurers, creditors or shareholders in each of the three largest insurer insolvency conservatorship proceedings in recent years - the Mission Insurance, Executive Life and Golden Eagle conservatorships.</li></ul>
<P><b>Environmental</b></P>
<P>Our environmental practice involves litigation before state and federal courts and in administrative proceedings.&nbsp; For example, we represented the successor to Chris-Craft Industries, Inc. in natural resource damages and Superfund matters involving the after-effects of DDT and its impact on the Southern California environment.&nbsp; Our practice also involves regulatory counseling and agency advocacy; environmental audits and compliance; transactional work, both domestically and internationally; and advice on international environmental trade and development issues.&nbsp; We handle numerous due diligence reviews of potential environmental liabilities for major corporate, energy and real estate clients.&nbsp; We also advise clients with respect to their compliance obligations and potential liability under all of the federal environmental statutes, as well as state laws.</P>
<P><b>Franchise Law</b></P>
<P>Los Angeles litigators represent major franchisors and distribution companies in matters involving antitrust violations, business torts, contracts, federal and state franchise laws, breach of the covenant of good faith and fair dealing, intellectual property, employment-related issues, multibranding, advertising and purchasing cooperatives, new product introduction and re-franchising.&nbsp; Examples of franchise clients include:&nbsp; YUM! Brands, Inc. (KFC Corporation, Pizza Hut, Inc. and Taco Bell Corp.), USFilter Corporation, Alfa Romeo, Inc., Ferrari North America Inc. and Fiat U.S.A., Inc.</P> 
			<P>
	</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
